  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>

        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="AN164-kilavi">pācaṟaikkaṇṇirunta talaimakaṉ taṉṉeñciṟkuc colliyatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">What HE who was in the war camp said to his heart.</p>
        </div>
        <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="AN164">
        <l><anchor n="1"/>katirkai yāka vāṅki ñāyiṟu</l>
        <l>paitaṟa teṟutaliṟ payaṅkarantu māṟi</l>
        <l>viṭuvāyp paṭṭa viyaṉkaṇ mānilaṅ</l>
        <l>kāṭukavi ṉetirak kaṉaipeyal poḻitaliṟ</l>
        <l>poṟivari yiṉavaṇ ṭārppap palavuṭa</l>
        <l>ṉaṟuvī mullaiyoṭu tōṉ<supplied>ṟi</supplied> tōṉṟa</l>
        <l>veṟiveṉ ṟaṉṟē vīkamaḻ kāṉa</l>
        <l>mevaṉkol maṟṟavar nilaiyeṉa <supplied>ma</supplied>yaṅki</l>
        <l>yirumpaṉi yuṟaikkuṅ kaṇṇō ṭiṉaiyā</l>
        <l>viṉṉā tuṟaivi toṉṉalam peṟūu</l>
        <l>mitumaṟ kālaṅ kaṇṭiciṟ pakaivar</l>
        <l>matiṉmuka murukkiya toṭicitai maruppiṟ</l>
        <l>kantukā locikku<supplied>m</supplied> yāṉai</l>
        <l>veñciṉa vēntaṉ viṉaiviṭap peṟiṉē.</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
        <l>This [is] the time indeed, look, (1a-c)</l>
        <l>when [she would] get [back her] old beauty, she who remains in an unpleasant state (10)</l>
        <l>of despair, with eyes from which big tears drop, (9)</l>
        <l>confused, thinking (8d)</l>
        <l>“After, because of the the sun’s bowing down with [its] rays for hands (1)</l>
        <l>[and] scorching so that [everything] green ceases, the growth hid [and] changed, (2)</l>
        <l>on the dark ground of vast area in which cracks had appeared, (3)</l>
        <l>while [now], because intense rain is pouring to face the beauty of the wilderness, (4)</l>
        <l>Malabar lilies appear along with jasmine with fragrant blossoms, (6)</l>
        <l>many together, so that bees are humming in groups, dotted [and] striped, (5)</l>
        <l>perfume prevails in the forest fragrant with blossoms, (7)</l>
        <l rend="indent8">what now [is] the state of him?” (8a-c)</l>
        <l>– if we were to obtain release(?) from the work of the king in hot anger, (14)</l>
        <l>with elephants that break post-beams with [their] tusks (13)</l>
        <l>on which the rings are ruined that demolished the entrance of the enemies’ fortifications. (11d-12)</l>
      </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
  </text>

